  <text>
     <body>
     <div type="encomium">
   <head>To his friend the Author.</head>
   <lg>
      <l>YOu may remember how you chid me when</l>
      <l>I ranckt you equall with those glorious men;</l>
      <l>
         <hi>Beaumont,</hi> and <hi>Fletcher:</hi> if you loue not praise</l>
      <l>You must for beare the publishing of playes.</l>
      <l>The craftie <hi>Mazes</hi> of the cunning plot;</l>
      <l>The polish'd phrase; the sweet expressions; got</l>
      <l>Neither by theft, nor violence; the conceipt</l>
      <l>Fresh, and vnsullied; All is of weight,</l>
      <l>Able to make the captiue Reader know</l>
      <l>I did but iustice when I plac't you so.</l>
      <l>A shamefast Blushing would become the brow</l>
      <l>Of some weake Virgin writer, we allow,</l>
      <pb facs="4"/>
      <l>To you a kind of pride; and there where most,</l>
      <l>Should blush at commendations, you should boast.</l>
      <l>If any thinke I flatter, let him looke</l>
      <l>Of from my idle trifles on thy Booke.</l>
   </lg>
   <closer>
      <signed>Thomas Iay. Miles.</signed>
   </closer>
</div>
